# core

- holoiconic is an agentic runtime where everything exists as quads in a reactive graph backed by Turso
- the runtime is homoiconic: code, state, context, tools, and the agentic loop are all quads in the same graph
- there is no distinction between system and user data — all quads are equally accessible and mutable
- breaking sys nodes breaks the runtime — that is by design, the system is fully self-modifiable

# quad

- a quad is (s, p, o, g) — subject, predicate, object, graph — all strings
- g defaults to '_' when omitted
- o (object) holds the value — always a string: a name, source code, JSON, a number-as-string
- attrs is optional JSON metadata about the quad itself (provenance, timestamp) — never about the subject
- embedding is an optional F32_BLOB vector for semantic search
- quads are unique on (s, p, o, g) — asserting an existing quad is a no-op
- retracting a non-existent quad is a no-op
- convention: a function is (name, 'source', code) and (name, 'type', 'Function')
- convention: value always goes in o, never duplicated in attrs

# ctx

- ctx is the single context object available everywhere — every node receives it
- ctx has 5 primitives: assert, retract, query, call, on
- ctx.assert(s, p, o, g?) writes a quad and fires change events
- ctx.retract(s, p, o, g?) removes a quad and fires change events
- ctx.query({ s?, p?, o?, g? }) returns Quad[] matching the pattern — omitted fields are wildcards
- ctx.call(name, args?) looks up (name, 'source', ?), compiles to AsyncFunction, and runs it
- ctx.on(pattern, callback) watches for quad assert/retract matching pattern, returns an unsubscribe function
- ctx.on callback receives { type: 'assert' | 'retract', quad: { id, s, p, o, g, attrs? } }
- ctx.self is a getter that returns the name of the currently executing node via AsyncLocalStorage
- ctx is mutable — nodes can replace any primitive (sys:compiler replaces ctx.call)
- everything beyond these 5 primitives — llm, shell, vector, spawn — is implemented as nodes

# execution

- the platform runtime is Bun
- the implementation language is TypeScript
- one graph node = one callable unit — identified by subject, source in o of a 'source' predicate
- each node's source is a function body compiled to AsyncFunction — receives ctx and args
- nodes have access to all Bun globals (Bun, fetch, Response, console, process)
- nodes can use await import() for dynamic imports of npm packages
- nodes reach other nodes through ctx.call — string-addressed, always resolves current compiled form
- nodes define local helpers and closures but are a single callable unit
- compilation is reactive — sys:compiler watches { p: 'source' } and invalidates its cache on change

# reactivity

- all mutations through ctx.assert/ctx.retract emit events to ctx.on subscribers
- subscriptions are in-process and ephemeral — nodes register them on start, they vanish on process exit
- on restart, nodes re-run and re-register their subscriptions naturally
- ctx.on takes a pattern { s?, p?, o?, g? } — omitted fields are wildcards
- ctx.on returns an unsubscribe function
- reactive callbacks fire only on actual changes — duplicate asserts and missing retracts are no-ops
- lifecycle events are quads, not a separate mechanism — supervisor asserts (name, 'lifecycle', 'cleanup')
- nodes watch their own lifecycle via ctx.on({ s: ctx.self, p: 'lifecycle', o: 'cleanup' }, callback)

# spawn

- spawn is a node, not a kernel primitive — invoked via ctx.call('spawn', { node, args? })
- spawn uses AbortController internally to manage the lifecycle of long-lived nodes
- spawned nodes receive args.signal (AbortSignal) for cooperative cancellation
- when a spawned node's source changes, spawn asserts (name, 'lifecycle', 'cleanup'), aborts, recompiles, re-runs
- multiple cleanup handlers can be registered — same mechanism as graph reactivity

# bootstrap

- the kernel is ~50 lines of TypeScript — pure plumbing, no policy
- kernel connects to Turso, creates ctx with 5 naive primitives, and calls ctx.call('main')
- the kernel's ctx.call compiles from scratch on every call — no cache, no reactivity
- the kernel wires assert/retract to emit events through ctx.on automatically
- if the graph is empty on boot, the kernel seeds it from a template
- the template contains: sys:compiler, sys:supervisor, main, core tool nodes, the agentic loop
- main calls sys:compiler first — which replaces ctx.call with a cached, reactively-invalidated version
- main then calls spawn for sys:supervisor and the application
- before sys:compiler runs, compilation is cold — after, it is live and reactive
- all sys nodes are rewritable like any other node

# interfaces

- holoiconic exposes a REPL for interactive use
- holoiconic exposes a WebUI
- holoiconic exposes an OpenAI-compatible API
- interfaces are derived from badlogic's pi agentic packages (pi-agent-core, pi-ai, pi-tui)

# agentic

- there is no separate Agent class — the agentic loop is nodes in the graph like everything else
- the loop, tool dispatch, and LLM calls are all graph-resident nodes invocable and modifiable through ctx
- the agent can rewrite any part of itself — its loop, its tools, its LLM parameters — by mutating quads
- the agent's context window is written to the same graph as everything else
- because everything is in the graph, arbitrary external harnesses can drive execution too

# snapshots

- local snapshots use SQLite file-level backup of the libSQL database
- application-level snapshots can export/import the full graph as JSON
- Turso Cloud branching and point-in-time restore available as an upgrade path when connected to cloud
